# I Submitted Multiple Bug Bounty Reports Before Finding My First Valid Bug. Here's Why I'm Glad I Did.

Link:https://medium.com/@rushivenkatadri/i-submitted-multiple-bug-bounty-reports-before-finding-my-first-valid-bug-7c3881003da0

When people think about bug bounty, they usually think about rewards.

$500 bounties.
Critical vulnerabilities.
Hall of Fame.

But nobody talks about the reports that don't get accepted.

Over the past few weeks, I've submitted multiple reports while learning web security. Some were marked Informative. Some are still under review. None of them have earned me a payout yet.

And honestly, I'm okay with that.

## The First Report Felt Different

Finding something interesting was exciting.

Submitting the report was harder.

I had to explain what I found, how to reproduce it, why it happened, and whether it actually created a security risk.

That's when I realized bug bounty isn't just about finding bugs.

It's also about explaining them clearly.

## "Informative" Isn't the End

When one of my reports was marked Informative, I was disappointed.

After reading the response carefully, I understood what I had missed.

The issue existed, but the impact wasn't strong enough for that program.

That taught me something important.

Finding unusual behavior isn't enough.

You also need to understand how much it really affects security.

## My Biggest Change

When I started, I kept asking:

*"Which payload should I try?"*

Now I ask:

*"What is this application trusting that it shouldn't?"*

That single question changed the way I test applications.

Instead of only looking at endpoints, I started looking at workflows, permissions, and business logic.

## Every Report Is Practice

Even reports that don't become valid are valuable.

Each one improves something.

- Better testing
- Better report writing
- Better understanding of application logic
- Better impact analysis

I may not have my first bounty yet, but every report makes me a better hunter.

## What's Next?

I'm still learning.

I'm still solving PortSwigger labs.

I'm still documenting my journey through GitHub, Medium, LinkedIn, and X.

My goal isn't just to find one valid bug.

It's to become the kind of security researcher who understands applications deeply enough to find them consistently.

I'm not there yet.

But every report gets me one step closer.

